<div class="pure-g">
  <div class="pure-u-3-4">
    <p>We collect the following types of data about our users:</p>

    <ul class="pure-g non-bullet-list">
        <li class="pure-u-1-2">
          {{input type="checkbox" name="identityData" checked=model.identityData}}
          <label>Identity (email/etc)</label>
        </li>
        <li class="pure-u-1-2">
          {{input type="checkbox" name="locationData" checked=model.locationData}}
          <label>Location</label>
        </li>
        <li class="pure-u-1-2">
          {{input type="checkbox" name="userBehaviourData" checked=model.userBehaviourData}}
          <label>User Behaviour</label>
        </li>
        <li class="pure-u-1-2">
          {{input type="checkbox" name="computerNetworkData" checked=model.computerNetworkData}}
          <label>Computer/Network</label>
        </li>
        <li class="pure-u-1-2">
          {{input type="checkbox" name="financialData" checked=model.financialData}}
          <label>Financial</label>
        </li>
        <li class="pure-u-1-2">
          {{input type="checkbox" name="otherData" checked=model.otherData}}
          <label>Other</label>
          {{#if isShowingOther}}
            {{textarea value=name cols="80" rows="6"}}
          {{/if}}
        </li>
    </ul>

    <ul class="non-bullet-list">
      <li>
        {{input type="checkbox" name="noData" checked=model.noData }} 
        We don’t collect any user data
      </li>
    </ul>

    {{#link-to "steps.step" 2 classNames="pure-button button-blue next-step-button"}}move along{{/link-to}}

    <div>
      <p>You don’t need a privacy statement then. No point in filling this out any further.</p>
    </div>

    {{yield}}
  </div>

  <div class="pure-u-1-4">
    <button type="button" class="pure-button button-black-on-white help-text-button">What should I list?</button>

    <div class="help-text">
      <p class="first-help-text-item">
        If there's a reasonable chance information can be used to identify a living person, it's considered &ldquo;Personal Information&rdquo; by New Zealand law (even if no names appear). The information doesn't need to be &ldquo;secret&rdquo; or &ldquo;sensitive&ldquo;—it just needs to be about them.
      </p>

      <p>Examples of personal information include,</p>

      <p>
        <strong>Identity information:</strong> <br />
        Name, username, email-address,  password, date-of-birth/Age, gender, etc
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Location information:</strong> <br />
        GPS Location, physical addresses, etc
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Behavioural information:</strong> <br />
        Interests, browsing habits, searches, contacts or associates, etc
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Computer/Network information:</strong> <br />
        Browser identifiers/fingerprint, IP address, network information, etc
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Financial information:</strong> <br />
        Credit card, purchase history, etc
      </p>

      <p>
        &hellip; many other things. The types of information that can identify someone can be very broad.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>



